Economic Modeling

Are Trade Deficits Bad?

Andrej Arpáš

12/16/2019

Introduction

This project aims at applying sound quantitative methods and data analytics in the realm of computational and mathematical statistics to economic output and the trade deficit and the extent to which it can or cannot be said that the latter is “bad” for the former.

Running a trade deficit is what happens when a country imports more than it exports. The converse of that is referred to as a surplus. Both phenomena are forms of a lopsided trade balance, somewhat broader measure of which is the current account. Standard economic theory is unambiguous that the trade deficit is something not to be worried about. This, however, does not appear to be how the trade deficit tends to be perceived by the general public or written about in many a media outlet. The objective of this paper, therefore, is to analyze those metrics that, in one form or another, pertain to the trade deficit, such as I(M)ports, E(X)ports, the Trade Deficit (X-M), GDP data to gauge economic output, and the unemployment rate for the past ten years, from 2008 to 2018. (The data is quarterly and therefore 2019 could not be taken into account seeing that the last quarter had not been reported yet.)

Research Question: “Are Trade Deficits Bad?”

The research question harkens back to the “infamous” econoimc identity Y = G + I + C + NX, where Y denotes output, G government spending, I private investment, C consumer spending, and NX stands for net exports or the difference between exports and imports. It is this last term of the identity that seems to make some believe that since one takes away imports in order to arrive at the Y figure, imports must be bad for the economy. This, however, is merely a book-keeping operation intended to ensure that the final figure not be overestimated. The subtracting is necessary lest imports are double-counted in all the other terms. (Imports are part of certain exports, the consumer spending, investments by companies and domestic manufacturers, and even government procurement allows for foreign-sourced components and so on.) Posing the question in such simplistic terms allows one to arrive at a falsifiable hypothesis and makes modelling more interesting.

Hypothesis & Methods

I shall begin by presuming the trade deficit is indeed bad for the economy. What does “bad” mean in this context? “Bad” will be defined by the data to hold up the following relationship: The greater the trade deficit, the lower the output and vice versa.

(As a corrolary, I will also be tracking unemployment rates over the same time span since unemployment seems to be frequently lumped together with lower economic output, i.e. as yet another victim of the oft-vilified trade deficit. However, since the two are indeed paired up in economic literature, unemployment is largely redundant as a measurement tool in order to study the relationship between the trade deficit and economic output since the output and unemployment could be considered almost complements of sorts in the sense that there might be overlaps in terms of what one may learn about the trade deficit by observing either of the two.)

For the purposes of this paper, output is the dependent variable, and it depends on independent variables in my models, such as the trade deficit, unemployemnt rates and so forth.

The metrics of interest will be estimates of the extent to which GDP/output is predicated on the trade deficit. Statistically significant findings (alpha < 0.05) of a positive association between the trade deficit and the GDP will be taken as indicative of the rejection of the null, and therefore a proof by contradiction that the trade deficit is actually “good” for the economy, i.e. conducive to economic growth.

In the Random Forests (RF) phase of my experiment, the output will be my estimand, estimated by my RF model (the estimator), and the predictions yielded by this model will be my estimates.

Data Description

The data comes from three primary sources. All data in this project describes the United States economy and comes from U.S. sources only.

GDP

Obtained from the Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA), the data pertains to the Real Gross Domestic Product, in chained (2012) dollars, seasonally adjusted at annual rates, raw and converted in billions in the RConsole. (2008-2018, quarterly.)

Imports/Exports

Source of this data is the United States International Trade Commission (USITC), Imports for Consumption, i.e. imports physically cleared through Customs (in Customs value), and Domestic Exports (FAS value - i.e. a measure of the total value), i.e. of U.S. or foreign origin if the latter have been significantly enhanced in value in the U.S. so as to be considered “domestic”. The data comes raw, parsed at the 2-digit level (HTS-2) and is downloaded as aggregate and subsequently converted in the RConsole to get billions. The USITC web interface displays the data as monthly and quarterly values are obtained by adding up the months.

Unemployent Rate

This data is reported monthly, in percent terms. Quarterly data is calculated using a mean of the monthly values. It is publicly accessible from the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) website.

Now, I may want to do a Boolean on whether there is a trade deficit (1) or not (0). Plus, let’s make another column and call is the TBalance to stand for the Balance-of-Trade, positive would mean Trade Surplus, and negative values would denote the sought after Trade Deficit.

e$TradeDeficit <- ifelse(e$"Exports_Q"-e$"Imports_Q">=0, 0, 1) # For the Boolean Trade Deficit: Y/N?

Running this operator and checking the df (data frame), one sees that the U.S. has had a continuous trade deficit for the entire observed period. Having thus confirmed what one might already have suspected, that is, that the U.S. has run a trade deficit the whole time, it makes more sense to create another vector which won’t be the Balance-of-Trade, but instead we shall hone in on the Trade Deficit. Specifically, its quantity/magnitude, i.e. I will be looking at the absolute value of the Trade Deficit. We shall call this column TradeDeficit_Size. (Let’s remind ourselves that the units are what they were for Exports/Imports, i.e. just $US.)

When the unemployment rate is within one percent of the full-employment level (i.e. 5%), for each additional billion dollar increase in the trade deficit, the GDP goes up by $23.312bn. (Statistically significant: 2.37e-10 ***.) There does not appear to be much difference within vs. without the bounds, though.

Seems like I’m using up too many degrees of freedom, i.e. the residual error term is iflated by having to estimate too many parameters, thus artificially causing the significance to plummet. (The parameter estimates oughtn’t to change all that much.) Let’s do fewer interactions and only where it makes sense. So, for instance…

lm7 <- lm(GDP_Bn ~ TradeDeficit_Size_Bn + UnemploymentRate_Q, data = e)
summary(lm7)

Adjusted R-squared: 0.7868. So, this is better than lm1. With every one percent increase in the unemployment rate, net all else, the predicted GDP goes down by ~USD 353.5bn. Now, compared to lm1, this model’s Adj. R^2 goes up while its p-value associated with the Trade Deficit goes down, though both remain statistically significant. According to this model, net all else, with each additional billion dollars in the trade deficit, the GDP goes up by ~$9.34bn** (stat. significant). What I should say here is that although accounting for the Unemplyment Rate did help explain away more of my data, while it lessened the Trade Deficit’s p-value and although still stat. signif. ostensibly chipped away at its predictiveness, these results should be viewed through the prism of the so-called difference version of the Okun’s Law, which is a proven concept in standard economic theory that describes how quarterly changes in the unemployment rate move hand-in-hand with the growth in real output. (The GDP data I have is real output.) So, we already know there is this relationship, which allows us to surmise that though we have the Trade Deficit capture the M part of the output identity Y = G + I + C + (X-M), the unemployment may be capturing fragments of the other elements so adding it into the model is like mirroring the GDP, a little bit like using the GDP to predict the GDP, just obtusely. Plus, we may overestimate the trade portion of the identity since both the Trade Deficit and the Unemployment Rate may be drawing on similar factors for their predictiveness. For my other models, I think it best to steer clear of the Unemployment Rate.

Phase #3: Panel Time Series:

One thing I haven’t taken into account yet is that I do have panel data, i.e. really a time series. It’s all just GDP, Trade Deficit ect., but different quarters. Let’s input that as a separate column.

Some cleaning…

I do however, for the purposes of this project, hone in on just one country (the U.S.), which would be my idnum in first differenced regression. It is therefore not necessary to do first differences. Instead of the First Differences then, let’s do something predictive, like Random Forests with time data.

Random Forests & Predicting:

Cleaning part… Creating Time Lags 1. So, going one quarter back to predict the current one… Using GDP in Q_(n-1) to predict GDP in Q_n:

#library(randomForest)
#library(caret)

set.seed(12152019) # Today's date.
e$Quarters_Num <- as.numeric(e$Quarters)
training <- e %>% filter(Quarters_Num<=33) # 44 observations * (7.5/10) = 33 observations
# to be committed to training.
#class(e$Quarters)
testing <- e %>% filter(Quarters_Num>33)
#install.packages("brant")
#library(brant)
rf <- randomForest(GDP_Bn ~ GDP_Bn_Lag1 + Quarters_Num + TradeDeficit_Size_Bn_Lag1 +
                     UnemploymentRate_Q_Lag1,
                   data = training, importance = TRUE, ntree = 1000, na.action = na.omit)

What’s the most important predictor?

imp <- as.data.frame(sort(importance(rf)[, 1],decreasing = TRUE), optional = TRUE)
names(imp) <- "% Inc. MSE"
imp
                          % Inc. MSE
GDP_Bn_Lag1                 26.77326
Quarters_Num                26.25556
UnemploymentRate_Q_Lag1     13.18544
TradeDeficit_Size_Bn_Lag1   10.48791

So, there are two conclusions to make here. One is that indeed, since all the trade deficit, the GDP, and the unemployment rate in some quarter_n are, apparently, to a large extend predicated on what the values for these variables were in quarter_n-1, i.e. the previous one. This is to be expected in a time series for data such as the one I have. The second takeaway is that the Unemployment Rate is again acting up as a reflector of some of the other GDP elements, thus this variable’s predictiveness/importance may easily be overestimated by the model.

which.min(rf$mse) # How many trees would suffice to get the smallest MSE?
## [1] 58

Apparently, 58 trees would be enough.

Predict and evaluate on the testing set:

y_hat <- predict(rf, newdata = testing)
defaultSummary(data.frame(obs = testing$GDP_Bn, pred = y_hat))
       RMSE    Rsquared         MAE 
1053.318136    0.380464  967.367506 
#RMSE.rf <- sqrt(mean((y_hat-testing$GDP_Bn)^2))
#MAE.rf <- mean(abs(y_hat-testing$GDP_Bn))

RMSE USD 1053.318136bn, so ~$1.1tn, which is worrying.

Ideally, we would like a smaller RMSE, but that would necessitate more data from more countries and possible some more variables to throw in the model and to be able to try new models, maybe first differencing.

Findings/Conclusions

I have found that the most sensible model to use for this analysis was an Ordinal Logit Regression, which delivered statistically significant resutls.

According to this model, for each additional billion dollar increase in the Trade Deficit, the logit associated with going up one quintile in the GDP category increases by ~0.08*** (stat. signif.), as opposed to a lower category, net of other factors. That is, the odds of the GDP going up one quintile, as opposed to a lower quintile, net of all else, inrease some 8.27%*** (statistical significance > 99.9%.). This would indicate a positive relationship between the trade deficit and the output. Further research is necessary to explore some other interactions and to iron out deficiencies in the panel time series predictivity of random forests given the nature of the present data. More countries would also have to be taken into account if generalizations were to be made. This, however, is a promising start.
